There&#39;s no concept of &#39;keyed stream&#39; in Java Stream API like in some Big Data processing pipelines, so you&#39;ll have to group the result first and stream the values again. 

```
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Test test1 = new Test(1, &quot;qweqwe&quot;, null);
    Test test2 = new Test(2, &quot;qweqwe&quot;, null);
    Test test3 = new Test(3, &quot;qweqwe&quot;, null);
    Test test4 = new Test(1, null, &quot;dfdsfg&quot;);
    Test test5 = new Test(2, null, &quot;dfdsfg&quot;);
    Test test6 = new Test(3, null, &quot;dfdsfg&quot;);

    List&lt;Test&gt; list = Stream.of(test1, test2, test3, test4, test5, test6)
            // collect to Map&lt;String,Test&gt; by ID
            .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Test::getId)) 
            // stream only the values: Stream&lt;List&lt;Test&gt;&gt;
            .values()
            .stream()
            // reduce by merging fields, assumes data is &quot;correct&quot;
            .map(i -&gt; i.stream().reduce((a, b) -&gt; new Test(
                    a.getId(),
                    a.getFirst() == null ? b.getFirst() : a.getFirst(),
                    a.getSecond() == null ? b.getSecond() : a.getSecond()
            // orElse new because reduce returns an optional in case there is no aggregation result, it won&#39;t ever happen if dataset is &quot;correct&quot;
            )).orElse(new Test())).collect(Collectors.toList());

    System.out.println(list);
}

@Data
@AllArgsConstructor
@NoArgsConstructor
public static class Test {
    private Integer id;
    private String first;
    private String second;
}
```

This does produce the result you require but it is a bit clumsy, and not efficient since the reduce operation has to create a new Test oject every time, I wouldn&#39;t say that it is more practical than just using the imperative approach.

You can achieve your result by using a single Stream `groupBy` and `reducing` collectors. On the other hand, finding out the first non-null value in Java is a bit clumsy (either use `Optional` or a ternary operator):

```java
Collection&lt;Test&gt; list = Stream.of(test1, test2, test3, test4, test5, test6)
	.collect(
			Collectors.groupingBy(Test::getId,
			Collectors.reducing(
					new Test(), 
					(a, b) -&gt; new Test(
							findNonNull(a.getId(), b.getId()),
							findNonNull(a.getFirst(), b.getFirst()),
							findNonNull(a.getSecond(), b.getSecond())))))
	.values();
```
```java
private &lt;T&gt; T findNonNull(final T... values) {
	for (T value : values) {
		if (value != null) {
			return value;
		}
	}
	return null;
}
```
